1

00:00:04,930  -->  00:00:07,570
When solving data problems,

2

00:00:07,570  -->  00:00:10,150
you likely do many complex things.

3

00:00:10,150  -->  00:00:11,610
But at the end of the day,

4

00:00:11,610  -->  00:00:16,450
you want to give your audience what they need to make your results actionable.

5

00:00:16,450  -->  00:00:19,750
Here are a couple of tips for showing off your results.

6

00:00:19,750  -->  00:00:21,910
First, know your audience.

7

00:00:21,910  -->  00:00:26,590
If you're too technical with your presentation when your audience is non-technical,

8

00:00:26,590  -->  00:00:28,390
you'll lose that audience.

9

00:00:28,390  -->  00:00:32,340
This won't lead to a great experience for them or you.

10

00:00:32,340  -->  00:00:35,630
Second, use pictures where possible.

11

00:00:35,630  -->  00:00:40,130
Often a graphic can display an idea better than words or numbers.

12

00:00:40,130  -->  00:00:43,010
When I'm presenting my work to my colleagues who

13

00:00:43,010  -->  00:00:45,990
work with data all day and who are very technical,

14

00:00:45,990  -->  00:00:48,425
I might present code, formulas,

15

00:00:48,425  -->  00:00:51,870
and rough sketches of ideas in a document or Jupyter Notebook.

16

00:00:51,870  -->  00:00:54,630
Alternatively, if I'm meeting with product managers

17

00:00:54,630  -->  00:00:57,750
and designers or presenting to the company executives,

18

00:00:57,750  -->  00:01:03,150
this same topic will likely live in slides with concise, clear ideas.

19

00:01:03,150  -->  00:01:06,255
Plots that clearly show the point of my ideas.

20

00:01:06,255  -->  00:01:11,145
Finally, I would share conclusions and recommendations of how to use the results.

21

00:01:11,145  -->  00:01:17,080
Many times, these conversations are less exploratory and more persuasive in nature.

22

00:01:17,080  -->  00:01:19,640
We should implement this product change

23

00:01:19,640  -->  00:01:22,840
and this is why should come from this conversation.

24

00:01:22,840  -->  00:01:25,460
In the first situation with my data peers,

25

00:01:25,460  -->  00:01:30,280
we might discuss the difficulties and different methods we could use to analyze the data.

26

00:01:30,280  -->  00:01:32,960
We discuss the pros and cons of each method,

27

00:01:32,960  -->  00:01:38,160
but these details aren't necessary for your final stakeholders in most cases.
